⸻

Final Principle

A conversation ends.

A mission continues.

The Compiler exists so that intent survives conversation, becomes coordinated action, produces durable assets, and leaves Pantheon more capable than before the mission began.

Every completed mission should make the next mission easier.

One final insight: I think the Compiler should eventually have profiles. The same mission compiles differently depending on the context.

For example:

* Research Profile → maximize discovery and evidence.
* Builder Profile → maximize execution and prototypes.
* Teacher Profile → maximize clarity and transfer.
* Entrepreneur Profile → maximize learning per dollar and speed to market.
* Strategist Profile → maximize long-term leverage and optionality.

That means Pantheon doesn’t produce one plan—it produces the best plan for the role and objective, while still using the same underlying operator kernel. I think that would make the Compiler one of the most reusable components in the entire architecture.